One option is that LAR is targeted to be more constant, because it drives light interception. Very high leaf areas lead to very shaded foliage (etc.). Other option is that this arises through the correlation with leaf lifepan. This is how Enquist \& Niklas explained it, but it is only true when all else is equal. In support, \citet{reich1992} showed positive correlation between leaf life span and total stand leaf biomass across diverse forest stands. Our results are certainly consistent with longer leaf lifespan leading to higher leaf biomass, because of the strong nearly 1/x correlation between LL and LMA ()

